         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translations</head>
            <div type="translation" source="#jmr-jbwp-rgg2003" xml:lang="en"><p>Perhaps a reference to Abraham</p></div>
            </div>
       
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>For the building, probably of the VI century, see Ward-Perkins, op. cit, 326-341</p>
            <p>Perhaps from the formula ἐν κολπω Ἀβραα. </p>
            <p> The name Abraham is clear - perhaps from a phrase such as SEG VIII 754 κ(υρι)ε θ(εο)ς ἀβραὰμ καὶ Ἰσαὰκ καὶ Ἰακὼβ from egyptian Thebes or in direct appeal to Abraham as in SEG VIII 240. Ἅγιε Ἀβράαμα βωήθεν τὸν δοῦλόν σου </p>
            <p> For Abraham in Christian inscriptions cf. Cabrol Leclerq and Reallex. f. Antike und Christian.</p>
         </div>
         
